<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www4.tomshardware.com/mainboard/02q4/021007/index.html">www4.tomshardware.com/mai...index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
that video card is fine<br>
<br>
dont even bother with a sound card.  the onboard sound of modern high quality mobo is as good as a high quality sound card, and you are paying for it anyway.  unless you are the uber audiophile, you cannot tell the difference.<br>
<br>
use ddr333 ram.  it is the best performance on the market right now (yes, it is better than the ddr400.)<br>
<br>
go AMD all the way.  get the fastest chip your budget can allow.  if you have to scrimp on a part though, scrimp here.  it is the easiest to upgrade, and the fastest to change in price (yeay amd/intel price war!!)<br>
<br>
whatever monitor looks best to your eyes on the display floor, but definatly get a flat CRT.  the flat crt makes an unreal difference in quality and glare (less eyestrain)  LCDs are just not good enough quality to use for video games yet, and are way more expensive than they are worth.<br>
<br>
use winXP pro.  pay the extra for the pro.  it is more stable than home, and will allow you to network more easily if you are building a home lan, or go to lan parties.<br>
<br>
few things you did not mention<br>
power supply:  get a high quality (enermax or antec) psu.  i cant describe how many powerfull systems i have seen that act like slugs cause they run on some cheap a$$ made-in-a-vietnamese-sweatshop 300 watt psu.  get at least 400 watts for the system you are talking about, and get a high quality brand<br>
<br>
hard drive:  you dont need a huge one, but get a good one.  i recomend the western digital with 8mb cache.  make your whole system run significantly faster<br>
<br>
get a good cpu cooler.  there are several out there,  just make sure it doesnt sound like a jet engine.<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www4.tomshardware.com/cpu/02q3/020916/index.html">www4.tomshardware.com/cpu...index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
if you are buying a new case, spend some time looking into that.  remember, if you get a really great case once, you can use it for your next 20 (or more) computers.<br>
<br>
zip drive can be convienient, especially if they have them at your school or work.<br>
<br>
